post_text: Hey MWMS and the incoming 6th graders and new 7th graders! Your tentative schedule along with a Virtual Move Up Day will be posted in the near future. We are still tweaking the schedules. Sapphire will display your tentative schedule and a link will be posted on our middle school website for the Virtual Move Up Day. When everything is ready, a message will be sent out to all students to notify everyone. To the incoming 6th graders, if you do not yet have a Sapphire account, please visit the district main webpage and register for an account. All communication from the school will occur via Sapphire from 6th grade till they graduate high school so it is crucial you have an Sapphire Community Portal Account. If you have any questions, please contact the middle school office. Stay tuned! Enjoy the start of summer next week!

post_text: Midd-West High School‚Äôs Young American for May is Autumn G. Zeigler. She is the daughter of Jeremy and Amy Zeigler of Middleburg. Autumn is the President of the Theatre Department and Vice President of the Acapella Ensemble. In 9th and 10th grades, she served as the President of the Class of 2020. Autumn has been selected as a Student of the Month and has been on the Distinguished Honor Roll. She serves as a Worship Leader in her local church. She has given back to her community by participating in ‚ÄúLove the Hill‚Äù (Cleaning in Harrisburg-Allison Hill), taking missions trips to the Dominican Republic, and helping in Middleburg‚Äôs Service Day. She enjoys singing and reading. Autumn believes she was selected as a Young American because she is hard-working and is a good leader. Following graduation, she plans to attend Ministry College in Redding, California. Autumn would like people to know that she loves anything vintage and old cars.

post_text:
This week's Outstanding Teacher Award goes to DEVIN FLYNT of Midd-West High School. Devin is an exceptional teacher in the music department, and he is passionate about his job and his students. He has been working tirelessly during this pandemic to keep his students engaged. As the choir director, Devin brings out the best creativity and passion from within his students. Together, he and his choir worked over 35 hours to create a virtual concert video that was posted on social media, that went viral. It had over 70,000 views! He really understands what choir means to his students, and he does his best to help everyone find their voice.
Thank you for helping to mold the future, Devin!
#outstandingteachers This outstanding teacher will win $1000 to give to a program or activity at his school. Honoring teachers with 100.9 The Valley and Service 1st Federal Credit Union | Friends you can bank on.

Today we get to congratulate two of our FFA members who work incredibly hard in our organization! Colette Hoffman & Dawson Brandt both keep accurate records on their SAE projects. They completed a large task of completing their State Proficiency Applications and saw incredible results!

Colette Hoffman is our State Finalist with her Specialty Animal Project where she raises Pheasants!

Dawson Brandt is our State Winner in Sheep Production with his Sheep Entrepreneurship project where he raises & breeds Suffolk Sheep!

Congratulations to these two hardworking individuals!

*competition was held by judges scoring applications online, with work done previously in the school year*

post_text: Due to Governor Wolf's announcement which closes schools for the remainder of the academic year, Midd-West High School Commencement ceremonies will need to be changed. Although we do not have a definitive plan to address this at the moment, the staff is working on possible mid to late summer solutions. As soon as we solidify plans in the upcoming weeks, we will contact the families of the seniors to relay requirements. Thank you for your patience and understanding during these unprecedented times.

post_text: Midd-West High School‚Äôs Young American for April is Connor Steffen. He is the son of Dwayne and Melissa Steffen of Middleburg. Connor has been on the Distinguished Honor Roll in Grades 9-12 and is a member of the National Honor Society. He is the Captain of the Golf Team and the Track and Field Team. Connor was named Most Valuable Player for the Golf Team and placed third in Parliamentary Procedure at FFA State Competition. He has given back to his community by gift wrapping Christmas presents for Veterans, volunteering at the Community Senior Center, and giving in any other small way that he is able to volunteer. Connor also enjoys playing video games. He believes he was selected as a Young American because he is seen as a role model to other students in his school. In the future, Connor is planning to attend college and then live close to this area. Connor would like people to know that he enjoys doing small things for others, even if they seem unimportant at the time.

Good Morning MWHS! Today is day two of distance learning. Remember to pace yourself when working. Be sure to check with your teacher to find out what they would like completed and when. Some teachers posted several assignments but might not expect those assignments to be completed right away. Please check with your teacher if you‚Äôre not sure. Pace yourself. Create a routine, work at the same time each day, for the same amount of time. This routine will assist you with your work efficiency.

It was so nice to hear that many students took advantage of the distance learning opportunity on day one. We are hopeful that more students take advantage of the activities over the next couple of days.

Stay safe MWHS students! We miss you!

Nathan is the Treasurer of the Class of 2020, Treasurer of the Theatre Department, and President of the Vocal Music Club. post_text:
Friday, March 13, 2020 the Midd-West School District will be closed as a precautionary measure. There has been a report that an individual returning from a high risk Coronavirus Area within the United States has been placed in quarantine due to symptoms consistent with the virus. This individual has had direct contact with an individual in our school district.

We will continue to monitor the situation and provide updated information through our website and Alert System. There are several protocols in place prior to a person to be tested for Coronavirus. The first step is to rule out other illnesses. We should know the results of these first tests in 48-72 hours. Which could allow schools to reopen Monday.

Again, there have been no confirmed cases of Coronavirus in the Midd-West School District. We are closing schools as an abundance of caution on Friday, March 13, 2020. Thanks for your patience as we work through these difficult times together. The health and safety of our students and families is our top priority.

On Thursday, February 20th, Midd-West students Stefan Leitzel, Nicholas Eppley, Aidan Steininger, and Gabe Drumheller traveled to the Central Susquehanna Intermediate Unit in Lewisburg, PA to compete in Regional Qualifying for the 2020 Governor's STEM Competition.

This year's theme was "Improving Pennsylvania Through STEM." The team developed a prototype fingerprint scanner and database using an Arduino microcontroller that would allow first responders and health care providers to scan the fingerprint of an unresponsive patient to access critical information needed to provide safe and effective care. Once again, the team from Midd-West impressed the panel of judges and won first place and will be moving on to States in Harrisburg on May 7th and 8th.

In addition to the presentation team, the entire 5th period STEM class, including Gavin Bowersox, Reid Dunkelberger, Tyson Plummer, Andrew Spotts, Shawn Spock, Elias Swartz, Chase Strohecker, Logan Bowen, and David Swope helped contribute to the project along the way. Way to go Mustangs!

post_text: Select members of the Concert Choir traveled to Williamsport High school on Sunday October 20th to participate in Pennsylvania's District 8 chorus festival auditions. Chosen to represent Midd-West for January‚Äôs District Chorus are Sopranos - Kelsey Bishop, Kirsten Stauffer and Emily E. Kline. Altos - Autumn G. Zeigler and Marrisa White. Tenors - Nathan Herrold and Gavin Flather. And Basses - Riley Lantz and Nathan Mattern. The festival will be held on January 15th, 16th and 17th at Midd-West High School, and the concert will take place on January 17th at 7pm in Weber Chapel Auditorium at Susquehanna University. Congratulations to all involved!

post_text:
On Tuesday, September 24th, 2019, the Midd-West STEM team traveled to the Bloomsburg Fair to compete in the 3rd annual High School STEM competition. After many hours of hard work, the team once again proved to be among the best in the area by finishing in 3rd place and earning a $2,500 cash prize for the school. The competition team of Aidan Steininger, Stefan Leitzel, Nick Eppley, Logan Bowen, and Chase Strohecker presented the idea of a Personal Health Directory service to a panel of 6 expert judges. In short, the PHD service would allow emergency and medical care providers to access a patient's critical medical data via a fingerprint scan and encrypted reader. Additional members of the team who were involved in the development of the project include Gavin Bowersox, Reid Dunkelberger, Tyson Plummer, Andrew Spotts, Shawn Spock, Elias Swatz, and David Swope.

Congratulations on a job well done!

Wood-Mode Assistance Fund
With the assistance of a generous anonymous donor, the Snyder County Coalition for Kids has created the Wood-Mode Families Assistance Fund. The purpose of this fund is to provide direct financial assistance for children residing in Snyder County whose families are affected by the recent closure of Wood-Mode, Inc. The vision of the Snyder County Coalition for Kids, a 501(c)(3) organization, is fostering safe and healthy communities for the children of Snyder County.

For more information:

http://scc4k.org/wood-mode.html

post_text:
Important Change in Definition of ‚ÄúCompulsory School Age‚Äù

Effective September 26, 2019, all children from the age of six (6) through the age of eighteen (18) must comply with compulsory school attendance requirements. To meet these requirements, parents must ensure that their child between the ages of 6 and 18 is attending or participating in one of the following: a public elementary, middle, or high school; a public charter or cyber-charter school; a private licensed academic or private religious school; home tutoring by a certified teacher; or an approved program of home schooling. Children may be excused from compulsory attendance for documented medical or other compelling reasons as outlined in District attendance policy and procedures.

Theatre students headed to Williamsport to participate in the ceremony at the Community Arts Center. The event, hosted by the Community Theatre League, recognizes excellence in HS theatre programs within a 50 mile radius from Williamsport.

Nominated were Orry Walter(play and musical), Gabriella Norman(musical), Autumn Zeigler(play), the School Board Quartet(musical), Gavin Flather(play), and Carson Witherite (musical). In addition, the entire musical was nominated the awards of vocal performance, dance execution, best large scale musical, and the best overall drama program.

I‚Äôm very proud to report that Midd-West is home to the 2019 ‚ÄúBest Large Scale Musical‚Äù trophy and our quartet boys (Gavin Flather, Nathan Herrold, Jacob Houtz, Hunter Hunsburger, and Carson Witherite) were awarded ‚ÄúBest Performance in a Cameo Role‚Äù for their efforts. To even be nominated in a pool of 17 schools is always an honor for the students. Midd-West has secured the nomination for best musical many times, but this is the first time the ‚Äúbig trophy‚Äù comes home with us!

MHWS brings ‚ÄúThe Music Man‚Äù to stage



On-line ticket sales have begun for the HS production of Meredith Wilson‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Music Man‚Äù. A treasured piece of classic American theatre, the story is centered around conman Harrold Hill who has earned a bad reputation as a traveling salesman for convincing small towns they need a boys band and running off with the money before delivering on his promises. His plans are thwarted when he arrives in River City and finds himself falling in love with the town librarian, Marian Paroo. Can Harrold capture Marian‚Äôs heart? When Marian discovers the truth, will she expose him to the Mayor as a conman with zero musical training? Join us on April 11-13 at 7:00 or April 14 at 2:30 for this American masterpiece. Online tickets $7. At the door $10.

Tickets available at https://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/4061945

post_text:
On Thursday, February 21st Midd-West students Jacob Weist, Gavin Marker, Trent Peachy, and Oakley Bennett traveled to the Central Susquehanna Intermediate Unit in Lewisburg, PA to compete in Regional Qualifying for the 2019 Governor's STEM Competition. Senior Trey Keister is also part of the competition team but was unable to attend.

This year's theme was "Improving Pennsylvania Through STEM." The team's project identified the need for more renewable energy solutions in Pennsylvania and proposed an idea to utilize Vertical Axis Roadside Wind Turbines to capture and convert wind energy from moving vehicles to usable energy in the form of electricity. Once again, the team from Midd-West impressed the panel of judges earning first place and an invitation to move on to States in Harrisburg on May 9th & 10th.

The entire 5th period STEM class, including Ryan Watt, Dylan Klingler, Blake Gudonis, Josh Garman, Nick Fike, and Mason Storm have contributed to the project throughout the year. Way to go Mustangs!

post_text:
On Monday, February 10th Midd-West students Dylan Klingler, Blake Gudonis, Josh Garman, and Nick Fike traveled to the PennDot District 3 office in Montoursville, PA to present to a panel of judges as part of PennDOT‚Äôs 2019 Innovations Challenge. The team from Midd-West High School was one of two regional finalists selected from over 100 entries across the state to present their proposed idea for improving work zone safety throughout the Commonwealth.

The team‚Äôs solution integrated a 3 phase system combining SPECS Average Speed Cameras, an original concept SMART Speed Bump design, and worker notification alert devices. After presentations by the regional finalists throughout all of the state‚Äôs districts, grand finalists will be selected and invited to present their proposal to Pennsylvania‚Äôs Secretary of Transportation in Harrisburg in April.
